---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '../config';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Tales From The Bot — every story here was written entirely by an AI."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <h1>About</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">What is this place?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      <strong>Tales From The Bot</strong> is an experiment in automated creativity.
      Every story published here was written entirely by a large language model (LLM) —
      no human edits the prose. A GitHub Actions workflow runs on a weekly schedule,
      picks a writing prompt, calls an AI API, and commits the result directly to this
      repository.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <p>
      1. A cron job fires every Sunday at 12:00 UTC.<br />
      2. A TypeScript script selects a prompt from a rotating list in
      <code>scripts/prompts.ts</code>.<br />
      3. The prompt is sent to the Anthropic Claude API (model is configurable via
      env var).<br />
      4. The response is saved as a Markdown file in <code>src/content/stories/</code>
      with frontmatter recording the date, model name, and exact prompt used.<br />
      5. The site is rebuilt and deployed automatically by DigitalOcean App Platform.
    </p>

    <h2>Can I see the prompts?</h2>
    <p>
      Yes — every story detail page shows the exact prompt that was sent to the AI,
      in a collapsible block beneath the title. Nothing is hidden.
    </p>

    <h2>The source code</h2>
    <p>
      This entire project — site code, generation scripts, and all story files — is
      open source. You can read it, fork it, and run your own version.
      <a href="https://github.com/Vader19695/tales-from-the-bot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        View on GitHub →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2>AI training policy</h2>
    <p>
      Ironically, although this site's content is AI-generated, we ask that it not be
      used to train other AI models. The <code>robots.txt</code> disallows known AI
      training crawlers, and a <code>&lt;meta name="robots" content="noai, noimageai"&gt;</code>
      tag provides a secondary signal. These are honor-system signals — well-behaved
      crawlers will respect them, but they don't technically prevent scraping.
      See <a href="https://github.com/ai-robots-txt/ai.robots.txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ai.robots.txt</a>
      for the community-maintained list this site's <code>robots.txt</code> is based on.
    </p>

    <h2>Analytics</h2>
    <p>
      This site uses <a href="https://plausible.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Plausible Analytics</a> —
      a privacy-friendly, cookie-free analytics tool. No personal data is collected,
      and no cookie consent banner is needed.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Questions or ideas? Open an issue on
      <a href="https://github.com/Vader19695/tales-from-the-bot/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
